<p class="">    <h1>Key Challenges in the Pancreatic Enzymes Market</h1>        <ul>        <li><strong>Regulatory Hurdles:</strong> The pancreatic enzymes market is subject to stringent regulations, which can affect the speed at which new products are developed and brought to market. Regulatory compliance requires substantial investment in research and development, delaying potential returns.</li>                <li><strong>Lack of Awareness:</strong> There is a general lack of awareness about pancreatic enzyme replacement therapy (PERT) among both healthcare providers and patients. This can lead to underdiagnosis or misdiagnosis of conditions requiring enzyme supplementation, stunting market growth.</li>                <li><strong>High Competition:</strong> The market is highly competitive, with numerous players offering similar products. This can lead to price wars, reducing profit margins for manufacturers. Differentiating products through innovation is essential yet challenging.</li>                <li><strong>Supply Chain Disruptions:</strong> Global supply chain challenges, particularly influenced by geopolitical tensions and pandemics, have resulted in inconsistent availability of raw materials required for enzyme production, affecting overall market stability.</li>                <li><strong>Patient Compliance:</strong> Ensuring patient compliance with prescribed enzyme therapies can be difficult due to factors like side effects and the complexity of treatment regimens. Non-compliance can limit the effectiveness of therapies and hinder market growth.</li>    </ul>    <h1>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Pancreatic Enzymes Market</h1>        <ul>        <li><strong>Technological Advancements:</strong> Innovations in drug delivery systems and formulations can improve the effectiveness of pancreatic enzymes, enhance patient convenience, and offer opportunities for product differentiation.</li>                <li><strong>Aging Population:</strong> The incr